During planetary formation, the interior was molten, allowing denser metals to sink toward the center due to gravity, while lighter silicates floated upward. This process, called **planetary differentiation**, explains why terrestrial cores are metal-rich. The other options either misrepresent physics (e.g., magnetic fields don’t draw metals) or are unsupported by evidence (e.g., metals weren’t delivered later or created by decay).
